<node TEXT="[1/5] 1. Symbol" FOLDED="true" ID="ID_1137704704" CREATED="1754249843410" MODIFIED="1754254360126">
<node TEXT="B.1.1 What is the role of a symbol in communication?" ID="ID_709994991" CREATED="1754249843410" MODIFIED="1754249843410" />
<node TEXT="B.1.2 How does a symbol differ from other parts of the semiotic triangle?" ID="ID_1110259885" CREATED="1754249843411" MODIFIED="1754249843411" />
<node TEXT="B.1.3 Why is a word or sign considered a symbol rather than a direct reference?" ID="ID_1212997367" CREATED="1754249843411" MODIFIED="1754249843411" />
<node TEXT="B.1.4 What if a symbol is ambiguous or unclear? How does that affect understanding?" ID="ID_588339756" CREATED="1754249843411" MODIFIED="1754249843411" />
<node TEXT="B.1.5 How do symbols help us organize thoughts or ideas?" ID="ID_1579445454" CREATED="1754249843411" MODIFIED="1754249843411" />
<node TEXT="B.1.6 What emotions can symbols evoke in an audience?" ID="ID_864753832" CREATED="1754249843411" MODIFIED="1754249843411" />
<node TEXT="B.1.7 How does the choice of symbol influence the meaning conveyed?" ID="ID_245398343" CREATED="1754249843411" MODIFIED="1754249843411" />
<node TEXT="B.1.8 What cultural factors shape the interpretation of a symbol?" ID="ID_890429782" CREATED="1754249843411" MODIFIED="1754249843411" />
<node TEXT="B.1.9 Why might different communities use different symbols for the same concept?" ID="ID_1637260764" CREATED="1754249843411" MODIFIED="1754249843411" />
<node TEXT="B.1.10 How can symbols be misinterpreted or lead to misunderstanding?" ID="ID_1139721267" CREATED="1754249843411" MODIFIED="1754249843411" />
<node TEXT="B.1.11 What role does repetition play in reinforcing a symbol’s meaning?" ID="ID_295957968" CREATED="1754249843411" MODIFIED="1754249843411" />
<node TEXT="B.1.12 How might an author deliberately use symbols to guide an audience’s response?" ID="ID_1864839274" CREATED="1754249843411" MODIFIED="1754249843411" />
</node>
<node TEXT="[2/5] 2. Reference" FOLDED="true" ID="ID_348265004" CREATED="1754249843411" MODIFIED="1754254392372">
<node TEXT="B.2.1 What does the reference represent within the semiotic triangle?" ID="ID_478469140" CREATED="1754249843411" MODIFIED="1754249843411" />
<node TEXT="B.2.2 How is the reference related to the symbol and the referent?" ID="ID_1177425916" CREATED="1754249843411" MODIFIED="1754249843411" />
<node TEXT="B.2.3 Why is the reference often called a concept or thought rather than a physical object?" ID="ID_1409262772" CREATED="1754249843411" MODIFIED="1754249843411" />
<node TEXT="B.2.4 How can different people have different references for the same symbol?" ID="ID_1843296351" CREATED="1754249843411" MODIFIED="1754249843411" />
<node TEXT="B.2.5 What if the reference changes over time—how does that affect communication?" ID="ID_269519310" CREATED="1754249843411" MODIFIED="1754249843411" />
<node TEXT="B.2.6 How does the reference shape our expectations about the referent?" ID="ID_267424745" CREATED="1754249843411" MODIFIED="1754249843411" />
<node TEXT="B.2.7 What emotional responses might a reference trigger in different contexts?" ID="ID_1770688849" CREATED="1754249843411" MODIFIED="1754249843411" />
<node TEXT="B.2.8 Why is it important to clarify the reference to avoid misunderstanding?" ID="ID_1014993328" CREATED="1754249843411" MODIFIED="1754249843411" />
<node TEXT="B.2.9 How does the reference function as an intermediary between symbol and referent?" ID="ID_236424046" CREATED="1754249843411" MODIFIED="1754249843411" />
<node TEXT="B.2.10 What role does cultural knowledge play in shaping references?" ID="ID_754712641" CREATED="1754249843411" MODIFIED="1754249843411" />
<node TEXT="B.2.11 How might a reference be intentionally ambiguous for rhetorical effect?" ID="ID_1653895420" CREATED="1754249843411" MODIFIED="1754249843411" />
<node TEXT="B.2.12 What if the reference conflicts with the actual referent? How is this tension resolved?" ID="ID_1143546610" CREATED="1754249843411" MODIFIED="1754249843411" />
</node>
<node TEXT="[3/5] 3. Referent" FOLDED="true" ID="ID_954747191" CREATED="1754249843411" MODIFIED="1754254415901">
<node TEXT="B.3.1 What is the referent in the context of the semiotic triangle?" ID="ID_1412350133" CREATED="1754249843411" MODIFIED="1754249843411" />
<node TEXT="B.3.2 How does the referent differ from the symbol and reference?" ID="ID_372425226" CREATED="1754249843411" MODIFIED="1754249843411" />
<node TEXT="B.3.3 Why is the referent often considered the 'real world' object or thing?" ID="ID_545927252" CREATED="1754249843411" MODIFIED="1754249843411" />
<node TEXT="B.3.4 How can a referent exist independently of symbols or references?" ID="ID_826812957" CREATED="1754249843411" MODIFIED="1754249843411" />
<node TEXT="B.3.5 What happens if the referent changes but the symbol and reference stay the same?" ID="ID_993020572" CREATED="1754249843411" MODIFIED="1754249843411" />
<node TEXT="B.3.6 How does the perception of the referent vary between individuals or cultures?" ID="ID_1148735423" CREATED="1754249843411" MODIFIED="1754249843411" />
<node TEXT="B.3.7 What emotional or symbolic significance can a referent carry beyond its physical reality?" ID="ID_1810762702" CREATED="1754249843411" MODIFIED="1754249843411" />
<node TEXT="B.3.8 How do referents influence the formation of new symbols or references?" ID="ID_136034600" CREATED="1754249843411" MODIFIED="1754249843411" />
<node TEXT="B.3.9 Why might the referent be absent or hypothetical in some communication contexts?" ID="ID_1824389710" CREATED="1754249843411" MODIFIED="1754249843411" />
<node TEXT="B.3.10 How does the referent contribute to the feedback loop in communication?" ID="ID_1057272323" CREATED="1754249843411" MODIFIED="1754249843411" />
<node TEXT="B.3.11 What if the referent is misidentified—how does this impact understanding?" ID="ID_26020210" CREATED="1754249843411" MODIFIED="1754249843411" />
<node TEXT="B.3.12 How might an author use an unexpected referent to challenge audience assumptions?" ID="ID_665280933" CREATED="1754249843411" MODIFIED="1754249843411" />
</node>
<node TEXT="[4/5] 4. Feedback" FOLDED="true" ID="ID_1595167637" CREATED="1754249843272" MODIFIED="1754254430356">
<node TEXT="B.4.1 What role does feedback play in the process of meaning-making?" ID="ID_6666933" CREATED="1754249843272" MODIFIED="1754249843272" />
<node TEXT="B.4.2 How does feedback influence the relationship between symbol, reference, and referent?" ID="ID_574351897" CREATED="1754249843272" MODIFIED="1754249843272" />
<node TEXT="B.4.3 Why is feedback important for effective communication?" ID="ID_1164523957" CREATED="1754249843272" MODIFIED="1754249843272" />
<node TEXT="B.4.4 How can feedback reveal misunderstandings or ambiguities in symbols?" ID="ID_1399868701" CREATED="1754249843272" MODIFIED="1754249843272" />
<node TEXT="B.4.5 What if feedback is ignored—how might that affect future communication?" ID="ID_830014187" CREATED="1754249843272" MODIFIED="1754249843272" />
<node TEXT="B.4.6 How do emotional responses function as a form of feedback?" ID="ID_1975215592" CREATED="1754249843272" MODIFIED="1754249843272" />
<node TEXT="B.4.7 In what ways can feedback lead to changes in symbols or references?" ID="ID_1627234129" CREATED="1754249843272" MODIFIED="1754249843272" />
<node TEXT="B.4.8 What kinds of feedback are most useful for clarifying meaning?" ID="ID_1851369298" CREATED="1754249843272" MODIFIED="1754249843272" />
<node TEXT="B.4.9 How does feedback contribute to the iterative nature of communication?" ID="ID_811634067" CREATED="1754249843272" MODIFIED="1754249843272" />
<node TEXT="B.4.10 Why might feedback vary across different cultural or social contexts?" ID="ID_912673903" CREATED="1754249843272" MODIFIED="1754249843272" />
<node TEXT="B.4.11 What if feedback contradicts the intended meaning of a symbol?" ID="ID_894360308" CREATED="1754249843272" MODIFIED="1754249843272" />
<node TEXT="B.4.12 How can feedback mechanisms be designed to improve understanding in communication systems?" ID="ID_744609787" CREATED="1754249843272" MODIFIED="1754249843272" />
</node>
<node TEXT="[5/5] 5. Revision" FOLDED="true" ID="ID_47753073" CREATED="1754249843272" MODIFIED="1754254446620">
<node TEXT="B.5.1 What is the purpose of revision in the semiotic process?" ID="ID_1299480086" CREATED="1754249843272" MODIFIED="1754249843272" />
<node TEXT="B.5.2 How does revision affect the symbol, reference, or referent?" ID="ID_1045283112" CREATED="1754249843272" MODIFIED="1754249843272" />
<node TEXT="B.5.3 Why might revision be necessary after receiving feedback?" ID="ID_1243270656" CREATED="1754249843272" MODIFIED="1754249843272" />
<node TEXT="B.5.4 How can revision improve clarity and reduce ambiguity in communication?" ID="ID_16878771" CREATED="1754249843272" MODIFIED="1754249843272" />
<node TEXT="B.5.5 What emotional impact can revision have on the audience or communicator?" ID="ID_1805044404" CREATED="1754249843272" MODIFIED="1754249843272" />
<node TEXT="B.5.6 In what ways can revision lead to new interpretations or meanings?" ID="ID_132031145" CREATED="1754249843272" MODIFIED="1754249843272" />
<node TEXT="B.5.7 How does the cycle of feedback and revision demonstrate the dynamic nature of meaning?" ID="ID_293007180" CREATED="1754249843272" MODIFIED="1754249843272" />
<node TEXT="B.5.8 What challenges arise during revision when symbols or references are deeply embedded culturally?" ID="ID_229609010" CREATED="1754249843272" MODIFIED="1754249843272" />
<node TEXT="B.5.9 How might revision alter the power dynamics in communication?" ID="ID_570484546" CREATED="1754249843272" MODIFIED="1754249843272" />
<node TEXT="B.5.10 What if revision introduces new ambiguities—how can these be managed?" ID="ID_636278071" CREATED="1754249843272" MODIFIED="1754249843272" />
<node TEXT="B.5.11 How can intentional revision be used as an authorial strategy?" ID="ID_1295504077" CREATED="1754249843272" MODIFIED="1754249843272" />
<node TEXT="B.5.12 Why is ongoing revision important for evolving languages or communication systems?" ID="ID_1837502535" CREATED="1754249843272" MODIFIED="1754249843272" />
</node>
</node>
<node TEXT="Intermediate" FOLDED="true" ID="ID_920112292" CREATED="1754249843147" MODIFIED="1754249843147">
<node TEXT="[1/5] 1. Symbol" FOLDED="true" ID="ID_1446100733" CREATED="1754249843147" MODIFIED="1754254360127">
<node TEXT="I.1.1 How does a symbol function as a mediator between thought and reality?" ID="ID_1890015384" CREATED="1754249843147" MODIFIED="1754249843147" />
<node TEXT="I.1.2 Why might the choice of symbol affect the interpretation of a message differently across contexts?" ID="ID_936205640" CREATED="1754249843147" MODIFIED="1754249843147" />
<node TEXT="I.1.3 In what ways can symbols carry multiple meanings simultaneously? How does this impact communication?" ID="ID_533590439" CREATED="1754249843147" MODIFIED="1754249843147" />
<node TEXT="I.1.4 How can the form and structure of a symbol influence its effectiveness?" ID="ID_1474358937" CREATED="1754249843147" MODIFIED="1754249843147" />
<node TEXT="I.1.5 What are the implications of symbolic representation for abstract versus concrete concepts?" ID="ID_1588519466" CREATED="1754249843147" MODIFIED="1754249843147" />
<node TEXT="I.1.6 How does cultural background shape the creation and interpretation of symbols?" ID="ID_280552862" CREATED="1754249843147" MODIFIED="1754249843147" />
<node TEXT="I.1.7 What are potential risks of relying too heavily on symbols in communication?" ID="ID_328987145" CREATED="1754249843147" MODIFIED="1754249843147" />
<node TEXT="I.1.8 How can the manipulation of symbols be used to influence audience emotions or perceptions?" ID="ID_1656318408" CREATED="1754249843147" MODIFIED="1754249843147" />
<node TEXT="I.1.9 Why is it important to consider the historical development of a symbol when analyzing its meaning?" ID="ID_429558986" CREATED="1754249843147" MODIFIED="1754249843147" />
<node TEXT="I.1.10 How might a symbol evolve over time through usage and reinterpretation?" ID="ID_877864836" CREATED="1754249843147" MODIFIED="1754249843147" />
<node TEXT="I.1.11 What if a symbol loses its conventional meaning—how does that affect communication dynamics?" ID="ID_236672177" CREATED="1754249843147" MODIFIED="1754249843147" />
<node TEXT="I.1.12 How does the intentional design of a symbol reflect authorial strategy or intent?" ID="ID_110427311" CREATED="1754249843147" MODIFIED="1754249843147" />
</node>
<node TEXT="[2/5] 2. Reference" FOLDED="true" ID="ID_85858398" CREATED="1754249843147" MODIFIED="1754254392374">
<node TEXT="I.2.1 How does the reference serve as an intermediary concept linking symbols to real-world objects?" ID="ID_1412580095" CREATED="1754249843147" MODIFIED="1754249843147" />
<node TEXT="I.2.2 What cognitive processes are involved in forming references from symbols?" ID="ID_957412296" CREATED="1754249843147" MODIFIED="1754249843147" />
<node TEXT="I.2.3 How can conflicting references for the same symbol lead to miscommunication?" ID="ID_1597112939" CREATED="1754249843147" MODIFIED="1754249843147" />
<node TEXT="I.2.4 In what ways can references be culturally or socially constructed rather than universal?" ID="ID_1335501630" CREATED="1754249843147" MODIFIED="1754249843147" />
<node TEXT="I.2.5 How do references evolve when new information or experiences modify existing concepts?" ID="ID_351816295" CREATED="1754249843147" MODIFIED="1754249843147" />
<node TEXT="I.2.6 What role does abstraction play in shaping references for complex ideas?" ID="ID_918939168" CREATED="1754249843147" MODIFIED="1754249843147" />
<node TEXT="I.2.7 How might references differ between experts and novices within a discipline?" ID="ID_1389798345" CREATED="1754249843148" MODIFIED="1754249843148" />
<node TEXT="I.2.8 How can ambiguity in references be strategically used in rhetoric or art?" ID="ID_1677207606" CREATED="1754249843148" MODIFIED="1754249843148" />
<node TEXT="I.2.9 What are the effects of reference mismatches in cross-cultural communication?" ID="ID_491649000" CREATED="1754249843148" MODIFIED="1754249843148" />
<node TEXT="I.2.10 How can clarifying references improve dialogue and understanding?" ID="ID_1236959211" CREATED="1754249843148" MODIFIED="1754249843148" />
<node TEXT="I.2.11 Why is it important to distinguish between a reference and a symbol in analytical reasoning?" ID="ID_1435185116" CREATED="1754249843148" MODIFIED="1754249843148" />
<node TEXT="I.2.12 How does the interpretation of a reference influence the audience’s emotional or cognitive response?" ID="ID_1037961182" CREATED="1754249843148" MODIFIED="1754249843148" />
</node>
<node TEXT="[3/5] 3. Referent" FOLDED="true" ID="ID_1289135480" CREATED="1754249843148" MODIFIED="1754254415902">
<node TEXT="I.3.1 How does the referent anchor the symbol and reference in tangible reality?" ID="ID_1556732452" CREATED="1754249843148" MODIFIED="1754249843148" />
<node TEXT="I.3.2 What challenges arise when the referent is absent or abstract rather than concrete?" ID="ID_1666255866" CREATED="1754249843148" MODIFIED="1754249843148" />
<node TEXT="I.3.3 How does the variability of referents across contexts complicate meaning-making?" ID="ID_1567340156" CREATED="1754249843148" MODIFIED="1754249843148" />
<node TEXT="I.3.4 In what ways can the perception of a referent be influenced by cultural or personal factors?" ID="ID_1419605465" CREATED="1754249843148" MODIFIED="1754249843148" />
<node TEXT="I.3.5 How do changes in the referent impact the stability of the symbol-reference relationship?" ID="ID_391365246" CREATED="1754249843148" MODIFIED="1754249843148" />
<node TEXT="I.3.6 Why might some referents resist symbolic representation or conceptualization?" ID="ID_1017235732" CREATED="1754249843148" MODIFIED="1754249843148" />
<node TEXT="I.3.7 How can an author use referents creatively to subvert audience expectations?" ID="ID_215362977" CREATED="1754249843148" MODIFIED="1754249843148" />
<node TEXT="I.3.8 What role does sensory experience play in identifying and understanding referents?" ID="ID_33606670" CREATED="1754249843148" MODIFIED="1754249843148" />
